50|$|New Zealand's <b>Sale</b> <b>of</b> <b>Goods</b> Act {{was passed}} in 1908 by the Liberal Government of New Zealand. It has been amended several times, {{including}} by the <b>Sale</b> <b>of</b> <b>Goods</b> Amendment Act 1961 and the <b>Sale</b> <b>of</b> <b>Goods</b> Amendment Act 2003.|$|R
50|$|Sections 16 was {{repealed}} by the Schedule to the <b>Sale</b> <b>of</b> <b>Goods</b> Act 1893 (56 & 57 Vict c 71). However its terms were substantially re-enacted as section 4 <b>of</b> the <b>Sales</b> <b>of</b> <b>Goods</b> Act 1893.Section 4 <b>of</b> the <b>Sales</b> <b>of</b> <b>Goods</b> Act 1893 was {{repealed by}} the Law Reform (Enforcement of Contracts) Act 1954.|$|R
50|$|The <b>Sale</b> <b>of</b> <b>Goods</b> (Amendment) Act 1994was enacted {{to abolish}} 'Marché ouvert' in 1995. (This Amendment made no other {{changes to the}} <b>Sale</b> <b>of</b> <b>Goods</b> Act).|$|R
